qas.question: Nearly all gasoline sold in the U.S. is mixed with what percentage of ethanol?
What act calls for 7.5 billion US gallons of biofuels to be used annually by 2012?
Name one company that sells flexible-fuel cars?
Nearly all gasoline sold in the UK is mixed with what percentage of ethanol?

plausible_answers.text: 7.5 billion US gallons (28,000,000 m3) of biofuels to be used annually

qas.question: What was the Energy Policy Act of 2004?
Name one company that sells nonflexible-fuel cars?

context: Nearly all the gasoline sold in the United States today is mixed with <a0_0><b3_0>10 percent<b3_0/><a0_0/> ethanol, a mix known as E10, and motor vehicle manufacturers already produce vehicles designed to run on much higher ethanol blends. Ford, DaimlerChrysler, and <a2_0><b6_0>GM<b6_0/><a2_0/> are among the automobile companies that sell flexible-fuel cars, trucks, and minivans that can use gasoline and ethanol blends ranging from pure gasoline up to 85% ethanol (E85). The challenge is to expand the market for biofuels beyond the farm states where they have been most popular to date. <a1_0>The <b4_0>Energy Policy Act of 2005<b4_0/><a1_0/>, which calls for <b5_0>7.5 billion US gallons (28,000,000 m3) of biofuels to be used annually<b5_0/> by 2012, will also help to expand the market.
